>>>>> atkinson@itd.nrl.navy.mil (Ran Atkinson) said:

> In article <22424p$rpb@src-news.pa.dec.com> leendert@src.dec.com (Leendert van Doorn) writes:

>>Another "small" problem is that solving the discrete logarithm problem (i.e.
>>computing the secret key from the public key) for the crypto system used in
>>secure RPC (Diffie Hellman & 192 bit keys) is relatively easy. 
>>Thus Sun's secure NFS has been broken since 1990 (perhaps even 1989, 
>>but I'm not sure about the dates).

>   Anyone have a good technical article reference for this "relatively
> easy" way to solve the discrete logarithm problem ??

>   An journal reference or conference proceedings reference would be
> helpful.

The references I have are:

@InProceedings{bal_sec_nfs,
  author =      "B. A. LaMacchia and A. M. Odlyzko",
  title =       "Computation of Discrete Logarithms in Prime Fields",
  booktitle =   "Advances in Cryptology- CRYPTO '90",
  year =        "1990",
  editor =      "A.J. Menezes and S.A. Vanstone",
  pages =       "616--618",
  publisher =   "Springer-Verlag",
  Note =        "Extended Abstract"
}

@InProceedings{bal_logs,
  author =      "B. A. LaMacchia and A. M. Odlyzko",
  title =       "Solving Large Sparse Linear Systems Over Finite Fields",
  booktitle =   "Advances in Cryptology- CRYPTO '90",
  year =        "1990",
  editor =      "A.J. Menezes and S.A. Vanstone",
  pages =       "109--133",
  publisher =   "Springer-Verlag"
}

According to the copy of the paper I have, the full text of the first paper
was to appear in _Designs, Codes, and Cryptography_ 1, 1991, though I don't
have a copy/confirmation of that.


